        <h2>Spring 2025: SB 1507 Signed, Oversight Office Launches</h2>
        <p>On March 21, 2025, Governor Katie Hobbs signed SB 1507, establishing the Office of Independent Correctional Ombudsman. The bill, prime-sponsored by Sen. Shawnna Bolick (R-District 20) with support from Sen. Analise Ortiz (D-District 24), creates an autonomous oversight body with investigation authority, record access, and facility inspection powers. Our <strong>Independent Prison Oversight</strong> team provided key testimony and will publish its first parallel inspection report in June, focusing on ASPC-Perryville with interviews from 50 incarcerated women.</p>
        <p>In legislative news, our coalition's work during the ADCRR Sunset Review prevented the agency from obscuring constitutional violations. Despite ADCRR's $1.77 billion budget and $30 million spent on private legal defense, federal courts have held them accountable for violating Eighth Amendment rights. Our <strong>Criminal Legal System Reform</strong> team continues pushing for probation reform and sentencing reform in the 2026 session.</p>
        <p>Our <strong>ARTS in Prison & Think Motion</strong> program received national attention for its peer-led workshops. The program currently operates in multiple facilities, with teaching artists—most formerly incarcerated—facilitating music, visual arts, and movement classes that build skills for post-release advocacy.</p>
